01:09:17.950 --> 01:09:20.933
can't believe that these actually
exist, but they do exist,

01:09:21.910 --> 01:09:25.270
what happens is there's
a rebound in vasodilation

01:09:25.270 --> 01:09:29.240
after cooling, so cooling
causes vasoconstriction,

01:09:29.240 --> 01:09:33.280
and then after the cooling,
there's a rebound vasodilation

01:09:33.280 --> 01:09:36.750
and there's more infusion
of blood into the gonads.

01:09:36.750 --> 01:09:39.480
There's also an effect that's neural,

01:09:39.480 --> 01:09:41.390
so let me explain how this works

01:09:41.390 --> 01:09:43.500
because there are only
a few studies on this,

01:09:43.500 --> 01:09:45.220
none of which looking
at the frozen underwear,

01:09:45.220 --> 01:09:46.860
but that have looked at cold exposure

01:09:46.860 --> 01:09:49.060
and levels of androgens and estrogens,

01:09:49.060 --> 01:09:50.630
and it's kind of interesting,

01:09:50.630 --> 01:09:53.890
so you have to remember that the gonad,

01:09:53.890 --> 01:09:57.590
the ovaries and the testes
are heavily vascularized.

01:09:57.590 --> 01:09:59.540
Remember, even at the level of the brain,

01:09:59.540 --> 01:10:01.810
GnRH, gonadotropin-releasing hormone,

01:10:01.810 --> 01:10:03.990
comes from neurons
that, believe it or not,

01:10:03.990 --> 01:10:06.150
start off in your nose
early in development,

01:10:06.150 --> 01:10:07.660
migrate into the hypothalamus.

01:10:07.660 --> 01:10:09.300
I'm not making that up, they
started off in your nose

01:10:09.300 --> 01:10:10.970
and migrated to the hypothalamus.

01:10:10.970 --> 01:10:14.700
Those neurons extend
processes, we call them axons,

01:10:14.700 --> 01:10:19.700
into the pituitary and release
GnRH into the pituitary.

01:10:19.760 --> 01:10:22.420
There's a lot of vascularization
within the pituitary,

01:10:22.420 --> 01:10:25.460
so now those hormones, or GnRH,

01:10:25.460 --> 01:10:27.880
can stimulate
follicle-stimulating hormone,

01:10:27.880 --> 01:10:28.830
luteinizing hormone,

01:10:28.830 --> 01:10:31.733
which then are released and
travel into the bloodstream.

01:10:32.970 --> 01:10:36.530
Then those hormones reach
the ovary or testes,

01:10:36.530 --> 01:10:39.410
and they have to get into
the ovary and testes,

01:10:39.410 --> 01:10:43.160
and the way they do that is
through the vascular system,

01:10:43.160 --> 01:10:45.960
and people forget, but the vascular system

01:10:45.960 --> 01:10:49.840
and how constricted or dilated vessels are

01:10:49.840 --> 01:10:53.580
is controlled by neurons, all right?

01:10:53.580 --> 01:10:55.640
We discussed this during
the discussion about stress

01:10:55.640 --> 01:10:57.310
in the stress episode,

01:10:57.310 --> 01:11:00.420
but it's well-known to neuroscientists

01:11:00.420 --> 01:11:04.340
that the best way to shut
down neurons is to cool them,

01:11:04.340 --> 01:11:06.470
so there are a lot of examples of this

01:11:06.470 --> 01:11:07.550
in the scientific literature,

01:11:07.550 --> 01:11:08.646
but most people aren't aware of it

01:11:08.646 --> 01:11:09.770
because you're not digging around

01:11:09.770 --> 01:11:11.340
in the method section of these papers,

01:11:11.340 --> 01:11:14.230
but when we want to shut down neurons,

01:11:14.230 --> 01:11:16.390
we can do things like inject
drugs that will do that,

01:11:16.390 --> 01:11:18.560
like lidocaine, you know,
the stuff that makes you numb

01:11:18.560 --> 01:11:19.393
at the dentist,

01:11:19.393 --> 01:11:20.860
or you can use different inhibitors,

01:11:20.860 --> 01:11:23.010
but one of the best ways
to do it experimentally

01:11:23.010 --> 01:11:24.370
is to just cool neurons,

01:11:24.370 --> 01:11:26.650
when you make neurons cold,

01:11:26.650 --> 01:11:28.300
because there's a temperature dependence

01:11:28.300 --> 01:11:30.640
of when neurons can be
active and when they can't,

01:11:30.640 --> 01:11:32.360
the neurons shut down,

01:11:32.360 --> 01:11:36.330
so the most plausible explanation
for why cold exposure,

01:11:36.330 --> 01:11:40.160
either through 1 to 10-minute
ice bath or cold shower

01:11:40.160 --> 01:11:41.870
or the ice underpants thing,

01:11:41.870 --> 01:11:45.150
would increase testosterone
or increase estrogen

01:11:45.150 --> 01:11:47.210
is that you're cooling the neurons

01:11:47.210 --> 01:11:50.470
that control vasoconstriction
and vasodilation

01:11:50.470 --> 01:11:55.270
and shutting down the entry of blood,

01:11:55.270 --> 01:11:56.680
or at least reducing it,

01:11:56.680 --> 01:11:58.940
and hormones into the gonad,

01:11:58.940 --> 01:12:02.230
and then when the gonad
and the surrounding area

01:12:02.230 --> 01:12:03.480
heats up again,

01:12:03.480 --> 01:12:06.350
you're getting a rebound
hyper-vasodilation

01:12:06.350 --> 01:12:09.810
that delivers excessive
levels of, not excessive,

01:12:09.810 --> 01:12:13.410
but increased levels of
GnRH and other hormones

01:12:13.410 --> 01:12:16.330
and carriers and carrier
proteins and so forth

01:12:16.330 --> 01:12:18.340
that would then stimulate the gonad

01:12:18.340 --> 01:12:20.130
to release more testosterone

01:12:20.130 --> 01:12:22.900
or would stimulate the gonad
to release more estrogen,

01:12:22.900 --> 01:12:25.710
that's the most plausible
explanation I can come up with,

01:12:25.710 --> 01:12:26.920
there aren't a lot of studies

01:12:26.920 --> 01:12:29.850
looking at direct effects
of temperature on the gonad,

01:12:29.850 --> 01:12:32.430
and it's going to be a
difficult study to carry out

01:12:32.430 --> 01:12:35.970
in any case because unless it
were done in vitro in a dish,

01:12:35.970 --> 01:12:38.080
it's very hard to eliminate
all the other things

01:12:38.080 --> 01:12:40.290
like vasoconstriction and vasodilation,

01:12:40.290 --> 01:12:42.940
put simply, we don't know
whether or not cold and heat

01:12:42.940 --> 01:12:47.690
directly affect the production
of testosterone and estrogen,

01:12:47.690 --> 01:12:51.340
we only know that cold and
heat can modulate those,

01:12:51.340 --> 01:12:53.100
probably through indirect mechanisms

01:12:53.100 --> 01:12:55.040
like controlling the amount of blood flow

01:12:55.040 --> 01:12:57.930
by way of shutting down
or activating the neurons.

01:12:57.930 --> 01:12:59.370
Now, there's a lot of lore

01:12:59.370 --> 01:13:01.613
around heating up the gonads too much,

01:13:01.613 --> 01:13:04.110
there's actually a whole set

01:13:04.110 --> 01:13:08.307
of pseudoscience webpages
out there saying,

01:13:08.307 --> 01:13:09.867
"Well, if you want a girl,

01:13:09.867 --> 01:13:12.627
"you should conceive the child
at this room temperature,

01:13:12.627 --> 01:13:13.460
"and if you want a boy,

01:13:13.460 --> 01:13:15.690
"you should conceive the child
at this room temperature."

01:13:15.690 --> 01:13:16.950
I don't think there's really

01:13:16.950 --> 01:13:20.490
any firm scientific evidence
for that, for either one,

01:13:20.490 --> 01:13:23.030
but there's some interesting literature

01:13:23.030 --> 01:13:26.310
about temperature dependence
of production of hormones,

01:13:26.310 --> 01:13:27.860
and I think that it probably relates

01:13:27.860 --> 01:13:29.690
to these mechanisms of vasodilation

01:13:29.690 --> 01:13:32.330
and neural control over vasodilation,

01:13:32.330 --> 01:13:34.350
and of course, excessively high heat

01:13:34.350 --> 01:13:36.740
is not good for the testes,

01:13:36.740 --> 01:13:39.030
for sperm production, or for sperm health,

01:13:39.030 --> 01:13:41.180
sperm have all sorts
of proteins in the cap,

01:13:41.180 --> 01:13:43.120
things like pentraxins and other things

01:13:43.120 --> 01:13:44.580
that cause them to swim faster

01:13:44.580 --> 01:13:47.290
when they're expressed properly
and in the right locations,

01:13:47.290 --> 01:13:50.250
and heat actually alters the
location and the function

01:13:50.250 --> 01:13:52.990
of a lot of those proteins,
they're very heat sensitive,

01:13:52.990 --> 01:13:54.360
and so that's why excessive heat

01:13:54.360 --> 01:13:56.820
is truly not good for fertility,

01:13:56.820 --> 01:13:59.350
which may be independent of heat's roles

01:13:59.350 --> 01:14:02.810
in promoting estrogen or testosterone.

01:14:02.810 --> 01:14:04.690
Okay, so now we've talked about breathing,

01:14:04.690 --> 01:14:06.240
light, and temperature,

01:14:06.240 --> 01:14:09.610
we talked about parenthood,
we talked about competition,

01:14:09.610 --> 01:14:11.930
and we talked about
some pheromone effects,

01:14:11.930 --> 01:14:15.160
now let's talk about
particular forms of exercise

01:14:15.160 --> 01:14:18.540
and how they modulate
the steroid hormones,

01:14:18.540 --> 01:14:22.130
and then we're going to talk
about various supplements,

01:14:22.130 --> 01:14:24.040
both in reference to testosterone

01:14:24.040 --> 01:14:26.070
and in reference to estrogen.

01:14:26.070 --> 01:14:29.680
So now let's talk about how
exercise in its various forms,

01:14:29.680 --> 01:14:31.180
weight training, endurance work,

01:14:31.180 --> 01:14:34.350
weight training to failure, or
less intense weight training

01:14:34.350 --> 01:14:36.880
can impact testosterone levels,

01:14:36.880 --> 01:14:39.570
but I want to remind you that
we're talking about testosterone

01:14:39.570 --> 01:14:41.540
both in males and females,

01:14:41.540 --> 01:14:44.520
and based on what you know
from earlier in the episode,

01:14:44.520 --> 01:14:46.990
testosterone can have
numerous positive effects

01:14:46.990 --> 01:14:50.230
in both males and females
provided they're in optimal range.

01:14:50.230 --> 01:14:52.980
So if you look on the web,

01:14:52.980 --> 01:14:55.000
people will say, "Oh, you know,

01:14:55.000 --> 01:14:57.147
"testosterone is increased
by weight training,

01:14:57.147 --> 01:14:59.030
"you want to do these big,
heavy compound movements,"

01:14:59.030 --> 01:15:01.320
squats and deadlifts and
chins and things of that sort,

01:15:01.320 --> 01:15:02.750
but what about the scientific studies?

01:15:02.750 --> 01:15:03.863
Like, what's the actual basis for this?

01:15:03.863 --> 01:15:05.610
Because if you just take a step back

01:15:05.610 --> 01:15:07.690
and look at this from the
perspective of a scientist,

01:15:07.690 --> 01:15:09.670
you'd say, okay, what is a squat?

01:15:09.670 --> 01:15:12.270
A squat is loading up a
bunch of weights on a bar

01:15:12.270 --> 01:15:14.310
and then, you know,
sitting down, essentially,

01:15:14.310 --> 01:15:16.110
and standing up over and over again.

01:15:17.030 --> 01:15:17.880
What's a deadlift?

01:15:17.880 --> 01:15:19.540
It's lifting heavy
weights from the ground.

01:15:19.540 --> 01:15:22.030
Why would that increase
testosterone, right?

01:15:22.030 --> 01:15:24.580
This is what's often not
discussed in the weight training

01:15:24.580 --> 01:15:26.270
or even the exercise science community,

01:15:26.270 --> 01:15:30.050
what would actually stimulate
the release of testosterone

01:15:30.050 --> 01:15:31.900
from the adrenals and/or testes,

01:15:31.900 --> 01:15:34.530
and which one is it,
adrenals or testes or both?

01:15:34.530 --> 01:15:36.010
And that's often not discussed,

01:15:36.010 --> 01:15:37.500
but as a neuroscientist,

01:15:37.500 --> 01:15:38.810
these are the kinds of
things we think about

01:15:38.810 --> 01:15:43.200
because we think always that
genes don't create behavior,

01:15:43.200 --> 01:15:45.350
immune systems don't know
when to be activated,

01:15:45.350 --> 01:15:48.270
lungs don't know when to inhale or exhale,

01:15:48.270 --> 01:15:49.570
hearts don't know when to beat

01:15:49.570 --> 01:15:52.510
except for the information
that it gets from neurons,

01:15:52.510 --> 01:15:54.950
the nervous system controls all of that,

01:15:54.950 --> 01:15:59.770
and so really the answer has
to be in the neural system

01:15:59.770 --> 01:16:02.250
that's related to these particular types

01:16:02.250 --> 01:16:04.260
of weight-bearing exercises.

01:16:04.260 --> 01:16:07.050
So when you go into this literature,

01:16:07.050 --> 01:16:09.740
it's kind of hard to find real mechanism,

01:16:09.740 --> 01:16:10.770
you see a lot of effects,

01:16:10.770 --> 01:16:13.410
you'll hear things like,
androgen receptor content,

01:16:13.410 --> 01:16:15.600
meaning testosterone and its derivatives,

01:16:15.600 --> 01:16:18.420
receptor content following
heavy-resistance exercise,

01:16:18.420 --> 01:16:19.710
and you'll find some examples

01:16:19.710 --> 01:16:23.330
that, for instance, you know,
they do muscle biopsies,

01:16:23.330 --> 01:16:26.140
they can actually see receptor increases,

01:16:26.140 --> 01:16:28.100
looking at either high-volume

01:16:28.100 --> 01:16:30.657
or low-volume really intense exercise,

01:16:30.657 --> 01:16:33.570
and you can find a lot of that
but not a lot of mechanism

01:16:33.570 --> 01:16:36.080
about how the nervous
system would do this,

01:16:36.080 --> 01:16:38.280
and the reason you'd want
to know how it can do it

01:16:38.280 --> 01:16:41.910
is that you could potentially
build better protocols

01:16:41.910 --> 01:16:45.440
or figure out exactly
what about these movements

01:16:45.440 --> 01:16:46.900
is triggering increases

01:16:46.900 --> 01:16:50.120
in androgen receptors and testosterone.

01:16:50.120 --> 01:16:52.960
So what's interesting is
when you start digging

01:16:52.960 --> 01:16:55.350
into the more mechanistic studies,

01:16:55.350 --> 01:16:58.390
what you find is that
heavy weight training,

01:16:58.390 --> 01:17:01.690
so this is weight training where the sets

01:17:01.690 --> 01:17:05.887
are done with anywhere from
kind of one to eight rep range,

01:17:05.887 --> 01:17:07.320
and this translates differently

01:17:07.320 --> 01:17:10.050
depending on ratio of muscle
fiber type and so forth,

01:17:10.050 --> 01:17:11.530
but where basically people are

01:17:11.530 --> 01:17:15.390
working at anywhere from like,
70% to 95% of their maximum,

01:17:15.390 --> 01:17:16.440
or sometimes even going

01:17:16.440 --> 01:17:18.430
right down to their
one-repetition maximum,

01:17:18.430 --> 01:17:21.210
really kind of max effort,

01:17:21.210 --> 01:17:25.490
what you find is that
using the nervous system

01:17:25.490 --> 01:17:27.780
in a way in which they're
moving heavy loads,

01:17:27.780 --> 01:17:30.070
so that I would translate to recruitment

01:17:30.070 --> 01:17:31.730
of high-threshold motor units,

01:17:31.730 --> 01:17:33.360
for you muscle physiologists,

01:17:33.360 --> 01:17:36.610
and there's a rule in muscle physiology

01:17:36.610 --> 01:17:39.390
about the neuron recruitment
for moving muscles

01:17:39.390 --> 01:17:40.660
where you basically use

01:17:40.660 --> 01:17:42.940
the minimum number of
motor units of neurons

01:17:42.940 --> 01:17:45.200
to activate muscle as you possibly can,

01:17:45.200 --> 01:17:46.740
as loads increase, you have to recruit

01:17:46.740 --> 01:17:48.510
more and more neurons,

01:17:48.510 --> 01:17:50.560
you always hear about
recruiting muscle fibers,

01:17:50.560 --> 01:17:52.290
but really, it's recruiting more neurons

01:17:52.290 --> 01:17:55.070
to recruit more muscle fibers,

01:17:55.070 --> 01:17:58.290
and what you find is that
heavy weight training,

01:17:58.290 --> 01:18:00.500
but not weight training to failure

01:18:00.500 --> 01:18:03.790
where completion of a
repetition is impossible,

01:18:03.790 --> 01:18:06.560
leads to the greatest
increases in testosterone.

01:18:06.560 --> 01:18:07.440
Now, I'm sure there are a bunch

01:18:07.440 --> 01:18:09.000
of exercise jockeys out there

01:18:09.000 --> 01:18:10.910
that are going to come at
me with a bunch of things

01:18:10.910 --> 01:18:13.180
where, oh, yeah, but high volume and this,

01:18:13.180 --> 01:18:16.640
and training to failure and that, sure,

01:18:16.640 --> 01:18:19.410
if you're willing to kind
of put things side by side,

01:18:19.410 --> 01:18:22.530
adjust for exogenous
testosterone treatment

01:18:22.530 --> 01:18:23.770
and all the rest,

01:18:23.770 --> 01:18:25.090
which was done in these studies,

01:18:25.090 --> 01:18:27.140
what you find in general

01:18:27.140 --> 01:18:30.410
is that weight training with heavy loads,

01:18:30.410 --> 01:18:32.140
so anywhere from one-rep maximum

01:18:32.140 --> 01:18:35.910
to somewhere in the six
to eight repetition range,

01:18:35.910 --> 01:18:37.750
in males or females,

01:18:37.750 --> 01:18:39.860
increases testosterone significantly,

01:18:39.860 --> 01:18:43.897
and it does it for about a
day, sometimes up to 48 hours,

01:18:43.897 --> 01:18:45.630
and the studies that I found

01:18:45.630 --> 01:18:48.830
which seem to hold the
most rigor or weight

01:18:48.830 --> 01:18:49.960
based on where they're published

01:18:49.960 --> 01:18:50.870
as opposed to being published

01:18:50.870 --> 01:18:51.880
in the journal of "Never Heard of It,"

01:18:51.880 --> 01:18:53.610
they're published in good-quality

01:18:53.610 --> 01:18:55.223
exercise physiology journals,

01:18:57.320 --> 01:18:59.910
for instance, the paper by Ratamess,

01:18:59.910 --> 01:19:04.070
R-A-T-A-M-E-S-S et al.,

01:19:04.070 --> 01:19:06.460
which was published in 2005,

01:19:06.460 --> 01:19:09.450
which talks about modulations
in androgen receptor content

01:19:09.450 --> 01:19:10.970
after heavy resistance exercise,

01:19:10.970 --> 01:19:13.610
looks at going to failure
and not to failure,

01:19:13.610 --> 01:19:18.610
the work of Izquierdo et
al. published in 2006,

01:19:18.817 --> 01:19:20.257
"Differential Effects of Strength Training

01:19:20.257 --> 01:19:21.827
"Leading to Failure Versus Not Failure

01:19:21.827 --> 01:19:24.440
"on Hormonal Responses,
Strength, and Power Gains,"

01:19:24.440 --> 01:19:26.010
you know, there are a lot of studies here

01:19:26.010 --> 01:19:29.550
and I will certainly put the
links to these in the caption,

01:19:29.550 --> 01:19:31.840
many of these actually
include Duncan French,

01:19:31.840 --> 01:19:34.200
who runs the UFC training center

01:19:34.200 --> 01:19:35.710
who I've had the privilege of meeting

01:19:35.710 --> 01:19:38.210
and discussing some of this with before,

01:19:38.210 --> 01:19:39.930
as well as other authors, of course,

01:19:39.930 --> 01:19:41.170
but they all point to the fact

01:19:41.170 --> 01:19:44.560
that there's something about
the engagement of the neurons

01:19:44.560 --> 01:19:48.550
that recruit high-threshold
motor units in muscle

01:19:48.550 --> 01:19:51.360
when moving heavy loads,
but not to failure,

01:19:51.360 --> 01:19:54.320
that has to provide some
sort of feedback signal,

01:19:54.320 --> 01:19:56.770
either to the gonad to
produce more testosterone,

01:19:56.770 --> 01:20:01.650
or is increasing the activity
of receptors in the body.

01:20:01.650 --> 01:20:03.260
Now, why do I say that?

01:20:03.260 --> 01:20:05.410
Well, this is the puzzle, right?

01:20:05.410 --> 01:20:06.930
How is it that a particular movement,

01:20:06.930 --> 01:20:09.340
just like how is it that
interacting with your child,

01:20:09.340 --> 01:20:11.780
is increasing or decreasing testosterone?

01:20:11.780 --> 01:20:13.270
This is the kind of fundamental question

01:20:13.270 --> 01:20:14.760
at the mechanistic level,

01:20:14.760 --> 01:20:17.140
and we answered the
question for child-rearing,

01:20:17.140 --> 01:20:19.710
it has probably something to
do with smell and pheromones,

01:20:19.710 --> 01:20:21.810
although I'm sure there
are other cues as well,

01:20:21.810 --> 01:20:26.060
but there's clearly a influence

01:20:26.060 --> 01:20:29.450
of hard work at the neural level

01:20:29.450 --> 01:20:33.160
and then at the muscular level
for increasing testosterone,

01:20:33.160 --> 01:20:37.430
and there's also clearly an
effect of working too hard

01:20:37.430 --> 01:20:40.320
and presumably increasing
cortisol too much,

01:20:40.320 --> 01:20:41.830
although I'm speculating there,

01:20:41.830 --> 01:20:44.390
in terms of reducing testosterone,

01:20:44.390 --> 01:20:46.930
and so the reason we're
getting nitty-gritty about this

01:20:46.930 --> 01:20:48.880
is because ultimately, we'd
really like to understand,

01:20:48.880 --> 01:20:50.270
what are the optimal protocols?

01:20:50.270 --> 01:20:51.460
You know, out there in the literature,

01:20:51.460 --> 01:20:54.510
you hear, move heavy objects
to increase testosterone,

01:20:54.510 --> 01:20:55.580
some of that will be converted

01:20:55.580 --> 01:20:57.550
to the more powerful androgen, DHT,

01:20:57.550 --> 01:20:59.710
by 5-alpha reductase et cetera,

01:20:59.710 --> 01:21:02.010
but we really don't understand yet

01:21:02.010 --> 01:21:04.770
how these particular behaviors
increase testosterone

01:21:04.770 --> 01:21:06.080
and whether or not it's doing that

01:21:06.080 --> 01:21:07.660
by modulating the receptors

01:21:07.660 --> 01:21:09.780
or it's modulating
testosterone release directly,

01:21:09.780 --> 01:21:11.620
presumably, testosterone release directly

01:21:11.620 --> 01:21:13.473
and sensitivity of the receptors,

01:21:13.473 --> 01:21:15.730
that what most of the
muscle physiology studies

01:21:15.730 --> 01:21:17.520
that I was able to find point to,

01:21:17.520 --> 01:21:18.840
but this basically boils down

01:21:18.840 --> 01:21:20.550
to a particular set of protocols

01:21:20.550 --> 01:21:22.670
where if you want to
increase testosterone,

01:21:22.670 --> 01:21:24.240
for whatever reason,

01:21:24.240 --> 01:21:27.790
that weight training with
heavy loads but not to failure

01:21:27.790 --> 01:21:30.390
seems to be the best-supported,

01:21:30.390 --> 01:21:33.420
at least scientifically
supported, solution to that,

01:21:33.420 --> 01:21:35.350
now, it may not raise
your testosterone levels

01:21:35.350 --> 01:21:36.430
as high as you want,

01:21:36.430 --> 01:21:39.690
but it's definitely taking
things in the correct direction.

01:21:39.690 --> 01:21:42.060
Now, many of you might
be endurance athletes

01:21:42.060 --> 01:21:44.560
or also enjoy exercise

01:21:44.560 --> 01:21:46.900
besides heavy-weight-bearing exercise,

01:21:46.900 --> 01:21:48.410
and there are several studies

01:21:48.410 --> 01:21:52.500
exploring whether or
not endurance activity

01:21:52.500 --> 01:21:55.860
can increase or decrease androgen levels

01:21:55.860 --> 01:21:57.300
and whether or not you combine

01:21:57.300 --> 01:21:59.150
endurance activity and weight training,

01:21:59.150 --> 01:22:00.720
whether or not that has any effect

01:22:00.720 --> 01:22:03.800
if you do the endurance
activity first or second,

01:22:03.800 --> 01:22:06.070
and the takeaway from all of this

01:22:06.070 --> 01:22:09.930
was that endurance activity,
if performed first,

01:22:09.930 --> 01:22:12.690
leads to decreases in testosterone

01:22:12.690 --> 01:22:14.560
during the weight training session

01:22:14.560 --> 01:22:17.220
as compared to the same weight
training session done first

01:22:17.220 --> 01:22:18.570
followed by endurance activity,

01:22:18.570 --> 01:22:21.470
in other words, if you want to
optimize testosterone levels,

01:22:21.470 --> 01:22:23.930
it seems to be the case
that weight training first

01:22:23.930 --> 01:22:27.420
and doing cardio-type
endurance activity afterward

01:22:27.420 --> 01:22:29.380
is the right order of business.

01:22:29.380 --> 01:22:31.010
Now, when these are done on separate days,

01:22:31.010 --> 01:22:32.310
it doesn't seem to have an effect,

01:22:32.310 --> 01:22:35.160
they showed no statistical interaction,

01:22:35.160 --> 01:22:37.050
but it seems that if
you're going to do these

01:22:37.050 --> 01:22:39.250
in the same workout episode

01:22:39.250 --> 01:22:41.470
that it's move heavy loads first,

01:22:41.470 --> 01:22:43.910
then do cardiovascular exercise,

01:22:43.910 --> 01:22:45.230
so there's a little bit of data

01:22:45.230 --> 01:22:47.860
looking specifically at
how endurance exercise

01:22:47.860 --> 01:22:50.620
impacts testosterone and its derivatives,

01:22:50.620 --> 01:22:53.200
and it's very clear that
high-intensity interval training,

01:22:53.200 --> 01:22:54.410
sprinting et cetera,

01:22:54.410 --> 01:22:57.190
which somewhat mimics the neural activity

01:22:57.190 --> 01:23:00.120
that occurs while moving
heavy weight loads,

01:23:00.120 --> 01:23:01.927
is going to increase testosterone

01:23:01.927 --> 01:23:04.830
and there's ample evidence
for that in the literature,

01:23:04.830 --> 01:23:09.620
and that endurance exercise
that extends beyond 75 minutes

01:23:09.620 --> 01:23:12.030
is going to start to lead to
reductions in testosterone,

01:23:12.030 --> 01:23:14.270
presumably by increases in cortisol,

01:23:14.270 --> 01:23:17.820
but of course, the
intensity of the exercise

01:23:17.820 --> 01:23:19.270
is going to be important too,

01:23:19.270 --> 01:23:21.900
you know, I don't think
anyone really believes

01:23:21.900 --> 01:23:23.190
that hiking for three hours

01:23:23.190 --> 01:23:25.280
is going to reduce your testosterone,

01:23:25.280 --> 01:23:27.420
whereas I think if one were to go out

01:23:27.420 --> 01:23:29.380
and run hard for three hours

01:23:29.380 --> 01:23:31.700
that you can imagine there'd
be reductions in testosterone

01:23:31.700 --> 01:23:34.580
by way of increases in cortisol,

01:23:34.580 --> 01:23:37.620
and so while this area
certainly needs more research,

01:23:37.620 --> 01:23:40.170
it's pretty clear that
limiting the endurance exercise

01:23:40.170 --> 01:23:43.140
to 75 minutes or less,
not making it too intense,

01:23:43.140 --> 01:23:46.710
is one way to keep cortisol
from going through the roof,

01:23:46.710 --> 01:23:48.280
but I've talked on previous episodes,

01:23:48.280 --> 01:23:50.070
and there are a lot of others
who have talked out there

01:23:50.070 --> 01:23:51.420
about how to clamp cortisol,

01:23:51.420 --> 01:23:53.580
how to keep cortisol more reduced,

01:23:53.580 --> 01:23:56.500
this is also one of the
reasons why, you can imagine,

01:23:56.500 --> 01:23:57.960
that various individuals,

01:23:57.960 --> 01:24:00.900
either for competition or
just for their own purposes,

01:24:00.900 --> 01:24:04.030
rely on testosterone therapy,
exogenous testosterone,

01:24:04.030 --> 01:24:07.550
not just for weight training,
but for endurance exercise,

01:24:07.550 --> 01:24:09.790
so this is one of the reasons
why every once in a while,

01:24:09.790 --> 01:24:11.310
professional cyclists will get popped

01:24:11.310 --> 01:24:12.870
for performance-enhancing drugs,

01:24:12.870 --> 01:24:14.060
meaning they'll get caught,

01:24:14.060 --> 01:24:16.670
and it's not just that they're
increasing red blood cells

01:24:16.670 --> 01:24:18.540
through EPO and things of that sort,

01:24:18.540 --> 01:24:20.530
oftentimes they're also
taking testosterone

01:24:20.530 --> 01:24:22.580
not because they want to be large

01:24:22.580 --> 01:24:25.020
or have massively hypertrophied muscles,

01:24:25.020 --> 01:24:28.110
but because they're
injecting testosterone,

01:24:28.110 --> 01:24:28.990
they don't have to worry

01:24:28.990 --> 01:24:31.477
about cortisol-induced
reductions in testosterone,

01:24:31.477 --> 01:24:32.810
and they can just clamp,

01:24:32.810 --> 01:24:34.390
or keep their testosterone levels high,

01:24:34.390 --> 01:24:35.810
not something I'm recommending,

01:24:35.810 --> 01:24:38.070
but I'm just justifying the rationale

01:24:38.070 --> 01:24:41.230
for why an endurance athlete
would want to do that at all.

01:24:41.230 --> 01:24:45.100
So now let's switch over
to talking about estrogen,

01:24:45.100 --> 01:24:46.140
so there are many people

01:24:46.140 --> 01:24:48.800
who are trying to optimize
their estrogen levels,

01:24:48.800 --> 01:24:50.820
and one of the places
where this shows up a lot

01:24:50.820 --> 01:24:53.630
and I get a lot of questions
about is menopause,

01:24:53.630 --> 01:24:55.490
so menopause, as I mentioned earlier,

01:24:55.490 --> 01:24:59.910
is this fairly massive reduction
in the amount of estrogen

01:24:59.910 --> 01:25:01.930
that is circulating in one's blood

01:25:01.930 --> 01:25:03.400
mainly because the ovary

01:25:04.300 --> 01:25:08.060
is now depleted of some
estrogen production of its own,

01:25:08.060 --> 01:25:09.760
the eggs are not being produced,

01:25:09.760 --> 01:25:12.030
they've been depleted, et cetera.

01:25:12.030 --> 01:25:15.660
So menopause is characterized
by a variety of symptoms,

01:25:15.660 --> 01:25:17.830
and it's multifaceted,

01:25:17.830 --> 01:25:20.090
probably deserves an
entire episode on its own,

01:25:20.090 --> 01:25:23.340
but things like hot flashes,
things like mood swings,

01:25:23.340 --> 01:25:26.630
things like headaches, in
particular migraine headaches,

01:25:26.630 --> 01:25:28.320
there can be a lot of brain fog,

01:25:28.320 --> 01:25:30.530
it can be very, very
disruptive for people.

01:25:30.530 --> 01:25:32.310
Now, you sometimes hear about andropause,

01:25:32.310 --> 01:25:35.150
which is thought to be the
kind of analog to menopause,

01:25:35.150 --> 01:25:37.440
but menopause has certain characteristics

01:25:37.440 --> 01:25:42.440
that make it a very robust
phenomenon for most women,

01:25:42.790 --> 01:25:44.670
whereas for men,

01:25:44.670 --> 01:25:47.580
andropause is going to sometimes
happen, sometimes won't,

01:25:47.580 --> 01:25:49.620
in fact, without going into the details

01:25:49.620 --> 01:25:51.910
of the graphs and the data,

01:25:51.910 --> 01:25:53.610
it's very clear, as I mentioned earlier,

01:25:53.610 --> 01:25:57.780
that some men maintain levels
of circulating androgens

01:25:57.780 --> 01:25:58.613
that are quite high,

01:25:58.613 --> 01:26:00.737
even as similar as they were in puberty

01:26:00.737 --> 01:26:02.640
and their teen years and 20s,

01:26:02.640 --> 01:26:04.670
well into their 60s, 70s, and 80s

01:26:04.670 --> 01:26:06.487
if they're optimizing
a lot of other things,

01:26:06.487 --> 01:26:09.220
and probably genetics
plays a role as well,

01:26:09.220 --> 01:26:10.970
whereas some males won't,

01:26:10.970 --> 01:26:13.660
but within the female population,

01:26:13.660 --> 01:26:16.370
or population of individuals
that have ovaries,

01:26:16.370 --> 01:26:18.880
there's a very stereotyped
and characteristic

01:26:18.880 --> 01:26:21.700
reduction in estrogen levels

01:26:21.700 --> 01:26:23.930
as the number of eggs becomes depleted,

01:26:23.930 --> 01:26:26.490
and that's what we think of as menopause.

01:26:26.490 --> 01:26:28.450
So what are the various things

01:26:28.450 --> 01:26:30.050
that one can do for menopause?

01:26:30.050 --> 01:26:32.660
Well, one of the most common ones

01:26:32.660 --> 01:26:36.060
is that physicians will
prescribe supplemental estrogen,

01:26:36.060 --> 01:26:37.810
so this is hormone therapy

01:26:37.810 --> 01:26:40.040
where somebody takes
either their oral estrogen

01:26:40.040 --> 01:26:42.100
or they'll use a patch or a pellet,

01:26:42.100 --> 01:26:45.500
some way to secrete
estradiol into the system,

01:26:45.500 --> 01:26:49.360
and that has varying success
depending on the individual,

01:26:49.360 --> 01:26:51.040
some people respond very well to it,

01:26:51.040 --> 01:26:53.310
other people really
have challenges with it,

01:26:53.310 --> 01:26:55.400
and there are a lot of side
effects associated with it

01:26:55.400 --> 01:26:57.660
for some people, not others,

01:26:57.660 --> 01:27:00.250
in addition, there's a concern always

01:27:00.250 --> 01:27:01.900
about supplementing estrogen

01:27:01.900 --> 01:27:06.200
when there's a breast cancer
background in the family

01:27:06.200 --> 01:27:08.250
or there's concern about
breast cancer for any reason

01:27:08.250 --> 01:27:11.150
because a lot of those cancers
are estrogen-dependent,

01:27:11.150 --> 01:27:15.210
and that's why drugs like
tamoxifen and anastrozole

01:27:15.210 --> 01:27:18.090
and drugs that block either aromatase

01:27:18.090 --> 01:27:21.320
or block, excuse me,
estrogen receptors directly

01:27:21.320 --> 01:27:23.060
were initially developed,

01:27:23.060 --> 01:27:24.610
you see them a lot on the internet,

01:27:24.610 --> 01:27:27.410
again, for all the sports folks

01:27:27.410 --> 01:27:30.290
who are trying to increase
testosterone, reduce estrogen,

01:27:30.290 --> 01:27:32.440
but remember, those drugs
were initially developed

01:27:32.440 --> 01:27:37.410
as ways to prevent estrogen
binding to the estrogen receptor

01:27:37.410 --> 01:27:39.180
as cancer treatments,

01:27:39.180 --> 01:27:40.610
so I want to be very clear

01:27:40.610 --> 01:27:41.740
and I've said this many times,

01:27:41.740 --> 01:27:44.830
we always put it in the caption
of each episode, of course,

01:27:44.830 --> 01:27:47.250
that I'm not a physician, I'm not an M.D.,

01:27:47.250 --> 01:27:48.170
I don't prescribe anything,

01:27:48.170 --> 01:27:49.610
I'm a professor and I profess things,

01:27:49.610 --> 01:27:51.190
I'm here to translate
the scientific literature

01:27:51.190 --> 01:27:52.380
and point to what might be

01:27:52.380 --> 01:27:54.760
some useful avenues for exploration,

01:27:54.760 --> 01:27:56.330
but this is just for information purposes,

01:27:56.330 --> 01:27:58.340
you should definitely talk to your doctor

01:27:58.340 --> 01:28:00.150
about anything that I'm talking about now

01:28:00.150 --> 01:28:02.430
or in any episode, for that matter.

01:28:02.430 --> 01:28:06.240
So if you look at the
literature on menopause

01:28:06.240 --> 01:28:10.160
outside of just standard estrogen therapy,

01:28:10.160 --> 01:28:12.940
there are some very
interesting compounds out there

01:28:12.940 --> 01:28:13.773
that have been used

01:28:13.773 --> 01:28:17.460
and that are supported by
quality peer-reviewed studies,

01:28:17.460 --> 01:28:19.450
and again, I'll refer you once again

01:28:19.450 --> 01:28:21.760
to this amazing website, examine.com,

01:28:21.760 --> 01:28:24.340
where you can put in
essentially any condition

01:28:24.340 --> 01:28:25.173
or any supplement,

01:28:25.173 --> 01:28:27.430
and it will point you to
the human effect matrix,

01:28:27.430 --> 01:28:29.440
not animal studies,

01:28:29.440 --> 01:28:32.220
but human studies that
have explored these things.

01:28:32.220 --> 01:28:34.380
Now, there are a huge variety of them here

01:28:34.380 --> 01:28:35.870
so I won't go into all of them,

01:28:35.870 --> 01:28:38.870
but some of the pro-estrogenic compounds

01:28:38.870 --> 01:28:42.240
that have been shown to be powerful

01:28:42.240 --> 01:28:44.360
in the context of menopause,

01:28:44.360 --> 01:28:46.340
as well as other conditions

01:28:46.340 --> 01:28:49.000
where estrogen is lower
than one would like,

01:28:49.000 --> 01:28:51.390
include a description in
some of the literature,

01:28:51.390 --> 01:28:52.410
I'll get into this in a moment,

01:28:52.410 --> 01:28:54.970
of something like black cohosh,

01:28:54.970 --> 01:28:56.600
I think that's the correct pronunciation,

01:28:56.600 --> 01:29:01.000
it's literally the word
black and then C-O-H-O-S-H,

01:29:01.000 --> 01:29:02.680
and it's very interesting,

01:29:02.680 --> 01:29:05.870
there are 13 peer-reviewed studies

01:29:05.870 --> 01:29:08.420
that have reached prominence

01:29:08.420 --> 01:29:10.090
in the kind of commercial landscape

01:29:10.090 --> 01:29:12.570
where this substance, black cohosh,

01:29:12.570 --> 01:29:15.170
has been promoted as a
way to increase estrogen,

01:29:15.170 --> 01:29:18.360
turns out that the effects are consistent

01:29:18.360 --> 01:29:19.530
but are fairly minor,

01:29:19.530 --> 01:29:22.290
fairly minor increases in estrogen,

01:29:22.290 --> 01:29:25.110
so it does seem to be a real effect,

01:29:25.110 --> 01:29:28.020
it is significant over the placebo effect,

01:29:28.020 --> 01:29:30.970
but there's also a
significant placebo effect

01:29:30.970 --> 01:29:32.740
in some of these studies as well,

01:29:32.740 --> 01:29:35.740
so what's interesting when
you look at these studies

01:29:35.740 --> 01:29:38.090
is that many of them were carried out

01:29:38.090 --> 01:29:40.430
over a period of six-plus months,

01:29:40.430 --> 01:29:42.350
they're double-blind studies, et cetera,

01:29:42.350 --> 01:29:46.860
and almost all of them lead to
modest increases in estrogen

01:29:46.860 --> 01:29:51.860
and modest decreases in
menopause-related symptoms.

01:29:52.290 --> 01:29:56.260
Now, a few additional
details about these studies,

01:29:56.260 --> 01:30:00.620
they were generally carried
out on women age 45 to 64,

01:30:00.620 --> 01:30:03.370
in some cases, they look
specifically at women

01:30:03.370 --> 01:30:05.200
that were clinically obese or overweight,

01:30:05.200 --> 01:30:07.070
although not always,

01:30:07.070 --> 01:30:09.320
the subject size pools are pretty big,

01:30:09.320 --> 01:30:12.120
you know, anywhere from 50 to 87,

01:30:12.120 --> 01:30:16.110
these are decent size,
132 subjects, et cetera,

01:30:16.110 --> 01:30:17.997
so these look to be like quality studies,

01:30:17.997 --> 01:30:20.360
and they basically point to
the fact that black cohosh

01:30:20.360 --> 01:30:25.080
can have a modest effect in
improving menopause symptoms.

01:30:25.080 --> 01:30:28.270
The other one is Panax ginseng,

01:30:28.270 --> 01:30:31.680
so P-N-A-A-X ginseng,

01:30:31.680 --> 01:30:33.380
has been shown to decrease some symptoms

01:30:33.380 --> 01:30:37.120
associated with menopause,
mostly related to libido,

01:30:37.120 --> 01:30:40.270
although the other
effects were unreliable.

01:30:40.270 --> 01:30:41.760
Other things, like maca,

01:30:41.760 --> 01:30:43.810
which is known to increase
dopamine actually,

01:30:43.810 --> 01:30:45.440
had minor effects,

01:30:45.440 --> 01:30:47.200
things like, the names here

01:30:47.200 --> 01:30:48.580
are a little hard to
pronounce, so forgive me,

01:30:48.580 --> 01:30:53.010
things like Valeriana officinalis

01:30:53.010 --> 01:30:55.860
has shown that there
can be some improvement

01:30:55.860 --> 01:30:57.470
in the hot flash symptoms

01:30:57.470 --> 01:30:59.400
and some of the insomnia
associated with that,

01:30:59.400 --> 01:31:01.230
so that might be worth exploring,

01:31:01.230 --> 01:31:02.750
again, discuss with your doctor,

01:31:02.750 --> 01:31:06.253
but these were both 100-subject plus,

01:31:07.410 --> 01:31:09.460
age 45 to 64 individuals,

01:31:09.460 --> 01:31:11.560
double-blind placebo-controlled studies

01:31:11.560 --> 01:31:14.680
that showed significant
but modest effects.

01:31:14.680 --> 01:31:16.930
There was one substance

01:31:16.930 --> 01:31:21.880
in the gallery of the
compounds that was looked at

01:31:21.880 --> 01:31:24.530
that turns out to be
particularly interesting,

01:31:24.530 --> 01:31:27.600
and this one is also particularly
difficult to pronounce,

01:31:27.600 --> 01:31:32.040
and it's Pueraria mirifica,

01:31:32.040 --> 01:31:33.810
so I'm going to spell this out for you,

01:31:33.810 --> 01:31:38.810
it's P-U-E-R-A-R-I-A, Pueraria,

01:31:40.164 --> 01:31:45.164
mirifica, M-I-R-I-F-I-C-A,

01:31:46.390 --> 01:31:49.140
and there are four
studies on this compound

01:31:49.140 --> 01:31:53.290
that show, in every case,
it to be very potent,

01:31:53.290 --> 01:31:56.130
in fact, comparable to estrogen therapy,

01:31:56.130 --> 01:31:57.950
estrogen replacement therapy,

01:31:57.950 --> 01:31:59.840
in reducing the symptoms of menopause,

01:31:59.840 --> 01:32:01.290
so this was pretty striking

01:32:01.290 --> 01:32:02.660
because when you go through these studies

01:32:02.660 --> 01:32:03.493
and you look again

01:32:03.493 --> 01:32:06.970
that they seem to be
pretty well controlled,

01:32:06.970 --> 01:32:08.770
as far as I could tell,

01:32:08.770 --> 01:32:11.633
and they explored a
pretty wide subject pool,

01:32:12.591 --> 01:32:16.180
and it seems that every
single one of these studies,

01:32:16.180 --> 01:32:21.180
when looking side by side
at Pueraria mirifica,

01:32:21.340 --> 01:32:22.880
which is also called,

01:32:22.880 --> 01:32:25.563
now this is really hard to
pronounce, Kwao Krua Kao,

01:32:26.420 --> 01:32:30.423
I guess that's the name that
they use in various countries,

01:32:31.340 --> 01:32:33.950
that it was comparable to
estrogen replacement therapy,

01:32:33.950 --> 01:32:36.940
so I mentioned this because
a lot of people contacted me

01:32:36.940 --> 01:32:39.137
and said, "What about the
insomnia in menopause?

01:32:39.137 --> 01:32:41.150
"What about the headaches in menopause?"

01:32:41.150 --> 01:32:42.620
Now, I'm not suggesting you run out

01:32:42.620 --> 01:32:44.380
and immediately start taking
any of these compounds,

01:32:44.380 --> 01:32:45.690
please talk to your doctor,

